===subject:And, also.
===from:Tim Fitzgerald
===date:Tue Jun 17 10:22:03 2003
===message:I tend to agree with everything you stated. 
<p>
In addition to the nationalism spawned in dominated countries in order to throw off the yoke of imperialism, a legacy of mistrust and hatred between nations, religions,  and ethnic groups is all too historically familiar. The familiar cry in Arab lands today is against the imperialism of the United States and Israel...a valid complaint in the past. Whether persent United States involvement in that part of the world is still imperialist in nature, or an evolved consciousness of equality and freedom from terrorism on a global scale has yet to be judged by history. The current issues facing that area of the world are most certainly the result of the imperialist policies of multiple nations. The legacy of violence and terrorism may remain for quite some time.
<p>
Almost all the wars in the last 200 years have been about nations trying to impose imperialist policies or throwing off the yoke of imperialism. Using the definition of imperialism from the discussion question then I would have to state that there is no justification for imperialism.
<p>
