===subject:response to Diane
===from:Heather Felice
===date:Tue Jun 17 14:19:12 2003
===message:I have to disagree with you on "Imperialism was all about greed."  I think that greed had something to do with it, but I also think that Imperialism had something to do with Social Darwinism.  "The strongest will survive."  Countries that were weak and unable to protect themselves from outsiders were taken over and used for their valuable resources.  You have to ask yourself this question also, are they better off now with all the advancements that have been introduced to them or before when they were underdeveloped, undereducated and not advanced enough to utalize their own resources?  
=========yorg=========
===subject:Response to Heather
===from:Laura Johnson
===date:Wed Jun 18  9:07:15 2003
===message:"Underdeveloped and undereducated" by whose standards? It is impossible to speculate how countries might have developed differently had they not come under imperial domination. Whence comes this idea that an agricultural or nomadic society is necessarily inferior? It is the ancient myth that those in power make the rules but need not abide them, that the winners write history, that "might makes right." 
=========yorg=========
===subject:Reply to Ramon
===from:Jordan Berkow
===date:Wed Jun 18 16:15:15 2003
===message:<p>I agree with you Ramon that a major drive for Imperialism was the domination and exploitation of the colonies recourses.  We read a small section on Religion and Political reasons, buy it is evident that most European powers had economic priorities in other lands.  An example of this was when Britain took control of India during the Mughal states declination.  The British had no intention of reviving the local governments there, but creating their own presence of government, all in the interests of trade and spices.  Another example is the British's transformation of Ceylon from a rain forest to a tea producing colony.  What is most noticeable is that they recruited Ceylonese women to handle the labor intensive work here.  It is only my speculation here, but I doubt these women wanted to live their lives in this area of work.  Both of these actions of Britain suggest that their primary interest was in the economic gain of that land area.</p>
<p>There is not a justifiable way to say Imperialism was right.  Many people died during war for these lands, so it is difficult to explain how any Country is just in oppressing another nation.  Most of these countries have gained their freedom today, but only after centuries of oppression and suffering of their past people.  It is true that history has revolved around issues of imperialism.  The greater country will try to get what it wants from a lesser nation, even by the means of force and war.</p>  

